1/31/2019

Background

We are currently conducting a 2-part randomized controlled trial on the impact of two programs in Samburu County, Kenya:

  • BOMA Project: provides women with business grants and two years of mentor support (plus health insurance).
  • Index-Based Livestock Insurance: satellite readings of NDVI (normalized differenced vegetation index) used to assess drought conditions, and payments are administered depending on drought severity.

Measuring the impact of each program individually as well as the two in combination.

Hypothesis: Insurance may help BOMA businesses survive droughts rather than be liquidated to pay for household expenses.

This Study

Theory suggests that households will make riskier decisions than their individual members would alone.

Intuition: risk is distributed within households, can be absorbed by less powerful members. This creates a mechanism that would make uninsured BOMA businesses more likely to liquidate in the event of a drought.

We design a tablet-based game to test this theory in two ways:

  • Directly, by playing the game individually and in couples.
  • Indirectly, by modifying how the game is presented to emphasize the fact that risk affects all members of the household.

Questions

Do couples make riskier decisions than individuals?

When we emphasize household risk sharing, do individuals change their behavior?

Household Models

Unitary model: household preferences can be represented by a single utility function. (e.g. Becker, 1981)

Cooperative models: partners may have unequal levels of power in household decisions, but they make decisions together. Outcomes are pareto optimal. (see Chiappori & Mazzocco, 2017)

Non-cooperative models: partners each make independent decisions taking into account how their partner might respond. Outcomes may not be pareto optimal.

Semi-cooperative models: Some decisions are made cooperatively, and some are made independently. (e.g. Lundberg & Pollack, 1996; Carter & Katz, 1992)

Gender and Preferences

  • In abstract risk experiments, men are sometimes found to be less risk averse than women.
  • With context (e.g. investment, insurance, gambling), differences tend to disappear.
  • The hypothesis that women are more risk averse than men is more often supported in the gain domain (investment, gambling) than the loss domain (insurance). (see Eckel & Grossman, 2008)
  • Cassar, Wordofa, and Zhang (2016) find that women are more competitive when they are competing on behalf of their children (rewards are paid in the form of bookstore voucher) than when they are competing for cash.

Theory

Theory based on standard cooperative model makes two main predictions about risk aversion:

  • The household will act less risk averse than an individual with the same level of income would.

  • If both members have the same underlying level of risk aversion, the more powerful member will make riskier decisions.

Theory: Household Utility

The household is cooperative, and divides `consumption' according to a sharing rule: \[ U(C) = \max_{c_1} \alpha u_1(c_1) + (1-\alpha)u_2(C-c_1) \] This leads to the first order condition: \[ \alpha u'_1(c_1) - (1-\alpha)u'_2(C-c_1)=0 \] The ratio of marginal utilities is constant.

Theory: Household Risk Aversion

By the envelope theorem, the derivatives of the household utility function \(U\) with solution \(c^*_1\) and \(c^*_2=C-c^*_1\) are: \[ \begin{align} U'(C) &= \alpha u_1'(c^*_1)\frac{dc^*_1}{dC}+(1-\alpha)u_2'(c^*_2)[1-\frac{dc^*_1}{dC}] \\ &= \left[\alpha u_1'(c^*_1) - (1-\alpha)u_2'(c^*_2)\right]\frac{dc^*_1}{dC}+(1-\alpha)u_2'(c^*_2)\\ &= (1-\alpha)u_2'(C-c^*_1) = \alpha u'_1(c^*_1) \end{align} \] and \[ U''(C)= \alpha u''_1(c^*_1)\frac{dc^*_1}{dC} \]

Theory: Household Risk Aversion

Combining the second and third derivative, we obtain the household's coefficient of absolute risk aversion:

\[ \begin{align}-\frac{U''(C)}{U'(C)}& = -\frac{u''_1(c^*_1)}{u'_1(c^*_1)}\frac{dc^*_1}{dC}\\ &=\text{Risk Aversion} \times \text{Marginal Consumption Share} \end{align} \] Since \(\frac{dc^*_1}{dC}<1\), this is smaller than either partner's independent risk aversion if their utility functions are the same.

The difference is greater for the less powerful agent under decreasing absolute risk aversion since their level of absolute risk aversion is larger and their marginal income share is smaller.

Theory: Power-Aware Risk Aversion

Suppose that each individual can make investment decisions on their own, but the proceeds are distributed according to \(U\). How does the individual value household income?

\[ v_i(C)=u_i(c^*_i(C)) \] which yields the risk aversion coefficient: \[ -\frac{v_i''(C)}{v_i'(C)} = -\frac{u_i''(c^*_i(C))}{u_i'(c^*_i(C))}\frac{dc^*_i}{dC} -\frac{\frac{d^2c^*_i}{d C}}{\frac{dc^*_i}{d C}} \] Under DARA, \(\frac{d^2 c_i}{d c_i}\) is positive for the more powerful agent - they take a larger share of household consumption as it increases.

The more powerful partner will make riskier decisions.

Predictions

  1. Individuals who making decisions alone will act more conservatively than the household as a whole does.

  2. The more powerful partner will make riskier decisions than the less powerful partner.

Intuitive interpretation: the household shares risk, and the less powerful partner bears the brunt of it.

Framing Insurance

Request from BOMA/ USAID: womens' insurance?

Droughts are the major risk facing pastoralist families, and costs are often born indirectly by women (as model above shows). BOMA businesses are at risk as well for this reason.

Can emphasizing indirect effects increase insurance purchase?

Testing the theory

The ideal experiment would randomly assign marriages and see how decisions change.

Instead, we test the theory in two ways:

  • By observing risky decisions separately and in couples.
  • By modifying our framing to increase the salience of risk shifting within the house.

Context

Samburu pastoralists manage camels, cows, goats, and sheep in a desert environment. Each year has two dry seasons and two (potential) rainy seasons. When the rains fall to arrive, it is considered a drought.

During the dry season, men travel with livestock in search of pasture. A few goats, sheep, or camels are potentially left at home to provide for family needs.

Traditionally a patriarchal society - women are generally not considered owners of livestock.

Game: Development

Dev Team

Designed as a simplified version of pastoralist life, with three key decisions: school, goats, and insurance. Goats were chosen because they are often managed by women and men in Samburu, unlike cows/ camels (usually men) or chickens (usually women).

Initially developed at UC Davis, revised substantially in the field based on extensive feedback from research team.

Experiment: Overview

387 couples, picked randomly from respondents in a subset of regions from our baseline survey.

Conducted by 4 teams who worked with groups of ~8 couples at a time across Samburu County.

Compensation: 300 KSh for attending plus incentive based on performance.

Experiment: Randomization

At the session level, we randomize framing and starting budgets.

Experiment: Framing

Livestock:

  • Droughts threaten livestock.
  • Insurance can help protect livestock.

Family:

  • Droughts threaten livestock and also make it hard to pay for household needs.
  • Insurance can help protect livestock and can also be used to pay household expenses, school fees, and more.

Individuals vs. Households

Regression: Individuals vs. Households

\[ D_{it} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 Woman_i + \beta_2 Man_i \\+ \beta_4 Budget_{it} + \beta_5 Budget_{it}^2 + \gamma_t + \epsilon_{it} \]

Intercept represents 'household' demand.

  • \(D_{it}\): Insurance/Goat Demand
  • \(Woman_{i}\): =1 if Woman
  • \(Man_{i}\): =1 if Man
  • \(Budget_{it}\): Total value of assets

Issue: budget is endogenous after first round.

Instrumental Variable

History of drought shocks is an ideal instrument, because we know for sure they are exogenous and they are strongly correlated with budget (First Stage F=53.75).

First stage equation:

\[ Budget_{it} = \sum_{i=1}^{t} \delta_t I_t FracGood_t + \sum_{i=1}^{t} \kappa_t I_t StartBudget_i + \text{controls}+ \mu_{it} \] where \(I_t\) is a year dummy, and \[ FracGood_t = \frac{\sum_{j=1}^t \omega_j}{t} \] where \(\omega_t\) is a dummy variable that is equal to 1 in the event of a good year and 0 in the event of a drought.

What have we learned?

Do households make riskier decisions than individuals?

Yes.

Do more men make riskier decisions than women?

Sometimes: in the livestock framing, yes. In the family framing, no.

Does framing affect demand for insurance?

Yes, though the negative effect for men is stronger than the positive effect for women.

Discussion: Economics and Identity

Akerlof & Kranton (2001)

Key concept: utility is over actions rather than over consumption, and actions have identity-linked costs and benefits.

This embeds utility functions over consumption, but also includes prescriptions - the idea that people may be subject to internally or externally-imposed costs for taking actions that conflict with what people with their identity are supposed to do.

Importantly, the social costs and benefits of a risky investment are probably more certain than the payout - similar to an increase in the insurance premium.

Next Steps

Discrete choice estimation of risk preferences:

  • Use maximum likelihood estimation to find CRRA utility function that best fits the full sequence data for each individual. To do this, I repeatedly approximate an expected utility solution to the dynamic game using TD(\(\lambda\)) approach from reinforcement learning - traditional approaches are prohibitive because the choice space is very large.
  • Initial result: women appear to be less risk averse than men or the household as a whole.
  • Next step: confirm reinforcement learning approximations are accurate using traditional approach (for smaller version of problem).
